[normal]Written evidence submitted by the Legal Aid Practitioners Group (JRR 0035)[bold]The Legal Aid Practitioners Group is a membership organisation for firms and organ
[normal]isations with a contract to carry out legal aid work. Our members are based throughout England and Wales and are both private practices and not for profit organisations. Our members carry out civil and criminal work and cover the whole range of sizes from 
[normal]small sole principal firms to some of the largest providers of legal aid services in the country. 
[normal]Introduction[bold]1. In response to the JCHR’s call for evidence, this document sets out evidence from the Legal Aid Practitioners Group (LAPG) in relation to hum
[normal]an rights issues raised by the following Government proposals relating to judicial review: 
[normal]              
[normal]a
[normal]. 
[normal]Standing and third party interventions [bold]– The proposed introduction of a narrower test for 
[normal]              
[normal]“standing” to apply for judicial review, so as to limit the range of 
[normal]people and groups who are 
[normal]              
[normal]entitled to invoke the procedure, and the proposed modification of the rules to discourage 
[normal]              
[normal]the involvement of interveners and third parties.
[normal]              
[normal]b
[normal]. 
[normal]Costs[bold] – The proposed rebalancing of financial incentives so that providers are only
[normal] paid for 
[normal]              
[normal]work carried out on judicial review cases where permission is granted, or exceptionally in the 
[normal]              
[normal]Legal Aid Agency’s discretion; and the proposed restriction on the availability of “Protective 
[normal]              
[normal]Costs Orders” which can currently be made by courts to limit the possible costs exposure for a 
[normal]              
[normal]claimant in a case judged by the court to be brought in the public interest.
[normal]              
[normal]c
[normal]. 
[normal]Procedural as opposed to substantive defects in decisions[bold] – The proposal to red
[normal]uce the 
[normal]              
[normal]potential for delay by strengthening the courts’ powers in cases where a procedural defect 
[normal]              
[normal]has been established which would have made no difference to the outcome had the correct 
[normal]              
[normal]procedure been followed.  The Government is considering lowering t
[normal]he probability threshold 
[normal]              
[normal]to include cases where it is not necessarily certain that the defect would have made no 
[normal]              
[normal]difference, and/or by bringing forward the point at which the “no difference” question is 
[normal]              
[normal]considered, so that applications for judicial revi
[normal]ew can be rejected on this basis at the 
[normal]              
[normal]permission stage.
[normal]              
[normal]d
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The Public Sector Equality Duty[bold] – The proposal to make non-
[normal]justiciable
[normal] the statutory duty 
[normal]              
[normal]imposed on public bodies by the Equality Act, to have due regard to the need to eliminate 
[normal]              
[normal]discriminat
[normal]ion, by providing an alternative, non-judicial mechanism for resolving disputes 
[normal]              
[normal]about whether public bodies have complied with the duty.
[normal]              
[normal]e
[normal]. 
[normal]The Committee also seeks evidence on the combined effect of these proposals and
[normal]:
[normal]              
[normal] (1) the Government’s proposals 
[normal]to reform legal aid, in particular the proposed 
[normal]              
[normal]introduction 
[normal]              
[normal]of a residence test and 
[normal]              
[normal](2) the provisions in Part 2 of the Immigration Bill reducing rights of appeal against 
[normal]              
[normal]immigration decisions.
[normal]2. LAPG notes that the Government’s latest proposals to 
[normal]make changes to judicial review are at variance with assurances made by Ministers to Parliament during the passage of the LASPO Act 2012 regarding the continued availability of legal aid for judicial review post-LASPO. For example, Ken Clarke gave an assur
[normal]ance that the Government would be “continuing legal aid in all cases involving judicial review”, and added that the Government “do not think that the Government or any public body should be resisting a claim about abuse of their powers from a litigant who 
[normal]cannot get legal advice” (Programme (No 3) motion, House of Commons, 17 April 2012, 
[normal]col
[normal] 227). The Civil Legal Aid (Merits) Regulations 2012 issued under LASPO Act provided a more robust test for availability of legal aid for judicial review cases and has a
[normal]lready restricted the availability of public funding.
[normal]a. Standing and third-party interventions[bold]3
[normal]. 
[normal]It is constitutionally important that there are proper checks on the decisions of public bodies and that where there is an issue of serious concern, cases ar
[normal]e able to be brought to shed light on the issues raised.
[normal] There is no evidence to suggest that the proposed changes are needed.
[normal]4
[normal]. 
[normal]T
[normal]here are already many hurdles to climb over to satisfy the current test of 
[normal]standing 
[normal]to bring a judicial review:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5
[normal]. 
[normal]There is no evidence that
[normal] numerous cases that have been brought just to seek publicity or hinder the process of proper decision-making.
[normal] Evidence from the Public Law Project suggests that only around 3% of j
[normal]udicial review final hearings involve “public interest” claimants (such as charities).
[normal] The current position on standing means that meaningful and important cases where nobody else could bring a case were properly raised before the Courts for determination 
[normal]e.g. the Medical Justice case
[normal] (
[normal]Medical Justice v SSHD
[normal] [2010] EWHC 1925 (Admin)
[normal]. 
[normal]6
[normal]. 
[normal]The role of third party interventions is important and helps to ensure that relevant arguments are put. Speaking
[normal] at the Public Law Project Conference 14 October 2013,
[normal] Baron
[normal]ess Hale indicated that she found the interventions in the cases before her helpful.
[normal]7
[normal]. 
[normal]We would reiterate what we stated in our
[normal] consultation
[normal] response
[normal]:
[normal] namely that these proposals raise very important constitutional issues. We are greatly concerned to see 
[normal]them put forward on an ad hoc basis in a relatively short consultation, in a time of considerable change.
