[normal]12
[normal]. 
[normal]A practical example is the calculation of 
[normal]a 
[normal]client’s means. This used to be carried out without too much d
[normal]ifficulty. 
[normal]Then 
[normal]legal help 
[normal]f
[normal]orms became longer. Regulations became lengthier. The LAA came under pressure from the National Audit Office on financial eligibility. More checks were carried out on file samples. Vulnerable, marginalised, chaotic clients now f
[normal]ace a major barrier to justice as they seek to prove their financial eligibility. What practitioners have absorbed is that they need to cut out all risk so if
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]for example,
[normal] a client with an emergency cannot prove their financial eligibility when they come 
[normal]to the office
[normal],
[normal] there is every likelihood that they will not be seen. Why? Because if the client fails to return with the correct documentation, the practitioner cannot claim any of the fee.
[normal]13
[normal]. 
[normal]The level of auditing and the huge cost to practitioners of de
[normal]aling with issues raised on audit means that it is unlikely that practitioners see the LAA as an agency that will exercise its discretion in favour of the practitioner. This concern has been highlighted by the LAA interpretation of when to grant exceptiona
[normal]l case funding. 
[normal]14
[normal]. 
[normal]It is unrealistic for legal aid practices to do this work ‘at risk’ and the amended proposal would not alter this. The practical effect is that 
[normal]a
[normal] case would not be brought in the first place because the legal team could not predict in 
[normal]advance what stage the case would reach.
[normal]15
[normal]. 
[normal]We would raise an added complication
[normal]:
[normal] namely 
[normal]that 
[normal]the current limitation on new matter starts for public law cases means that already existing providers have to ration legal help cases in public law. If the exis
[normal]ting 
[normal]limit on new matter starts
[normal] remains, then it will not be possible for providers to undertake work under legal help because 
[normal]they 
[normal]are insufficient
[normal]ly
[normal] allocated at present.
[normal]16
[normal]. 
[normal]Regarding Protective Costs Orders, 
[normal]we think that PCOs play an important part in
[normal] allowing matters of public interest to be considered by the judiciary and would oppose any changes. We refer to the analysis from the Public Law Project which makes it clear that there is no problem that needs to be tackled. The principles set out in the 
[normal]Corner House Case admirable and the Government has provided no information which gives c
[normal]ause for concern that frivolous 
[normal]cases could be brought. Nor has the Government indicated which cases it would class as ‘a campaign tool’.
[normal]17
[normal]. 
[normal]The Government has 
[normal]referred to inequality arising from PCOs but the bigger inequality is between those bringing the claims and those defending their actions. This is the true inequality of arms which needs to be addressed.
[normal]3. Procedural as opposed to substantive defects in d[bold]ecisions[bold]18
[normal]. 
[normal]There is no evidence that there is a problem that needs to be addressed. Certainly in legal aid cases the Legal Aid Agency would not fund legal aid for such a case unless the more onerous merits test is met, whether the challenge is based on p
[normal]rocedural defects or any other ground. Our understanding is that procedural issues may be raised along with other issues but we would again ask for evidence of these
[normal] purported
[normal] cases which are so numerous or severe that the current carefully thought out pro
[normal]cesses face being overturned.
[normal]4. The Public Sector Equality Duty[bold]19
[normal]. 
[normal]This is a summary of the points LAPG made in its consultation response:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5. The combined effect of these proposals and (1) the Government’s proposals to reform legal aid, in particular the proposed introduction of a residence test and (2) the provisions in Part 2 of the Immigration Bill reducing [bold]rights of appeal against immigration decisions.[bold]20
[normal]. 
[normal]In our view, it is unnecessary to make the proposed changes when there are so many mechanisms in place to protect abuse of the system.
[normal](1)
[normal] The residence test
[normal]21
[normal]. 
[normal]The proposal is to introduce a residence t
[normal]est in order to qualify for any level of civil legal aid, with two limbs: firstly to be lawfully resident in the UK, crown dependencies or overseas territories, and secondly to have resided lawfully in these places for 12 months. 
[normal]22
[normal]. 
[normal]The 
[normal]G
[normal]overnment has am
[normal]ended the original proposals
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]125. Having carefully considered consultation responses, we have concluded that 
[normal]              
[normal]there are further limited circumstances where applicants for civil legal aid on certain 
[normal]              
[normal]matters of law (as set out in Schedule 1 to LASPO) would not be required to meet the 
[normal]              
[normal]residence test. The test will not apply to the following categories of case (which 
[normal]              
[normal]broadly 
[normal]              
[normal]relate to an individual’s liberty, or where the individual is particularly vu
[normal]lnerable or where 
[normal]              
[normal]the case relates to the protection of children): 
