[normal]In our view the proposal is discriminatory and will affect large numbers of vulnerable people who will, if the proposal is i
[normal]mplemented, be at 
[normal]increased
[normal] risk of physical and mental harm
[normal], with no effective remedy
[normal].
[normal]28
[normal]. 
[normal]This provision – which the Government does not suggest will save money – will affect all clients because the test will have to be met by all those seeking advice un
[normal]less their case is clearly within the exceptions listed above. Many clients have no passport, will have difficulty with the first part of the 
[normal]test and will have difficulty providing the evidence that they have lawfully been here for a period of 12 months.
[normal]29
[normal]. 
[normal]Despite the concession, we believe that t
[normal]he proposal will also adversely affect vulnerable mentally incapacitated adults who currently have the protection of the powers of the Court of Protection.  
[normal]Paragraph 5 Schedule 1 LASPO Act covers cases other th
[normal]an detention as well as detention.  Will clients with cases within this category be exempt or not?
[normal]30
[normal]. 
[normal]Schedule 3 of the MCA 2005 deals with the International Protection of Adults with incapacity and sets out the scope of the Court of Protection's jurisdic
[normal]tion in relation to those adults at paragraph 7 of the Schedule.  Part 2 of the Schedule specifica
[normal]lly provides at Para 7(1)
[normal](c):
[normal]              
[normal]the court may exercise its function under this Act ( in so far as it cannot otherwise do so) in 
[normal]              
[normal]relation to:-
[normal]              
[normal]...
[normal]              
[normal]...
[normal]              
[normal](c) a
[normal]n adult present in England and Wales or who has property there, if the matter is 
[normal]              
[normal]urgent, or
[normal]              
[normal](d
[normal])
[normal] an adult present in England and Wales, if a protective measure which is temporary and 
[normal]              
[normal]limited in its effect to England and Wales is proposed in relation to h
[normal]im.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]These provisions appear to have been specifically added to include adults who would not otherwise meet the residency requirements of the Schedule. A typical case would be the removal of an incapacitated adult from another jurisdiction to England o
[normal]r Wales and an application to return the adult to the other jurisdiction. If the residence test as currently formulated is implemented then severely disabled persons who are at risk and require protection will be left without any remedy. This could in many
[normal] cases result in physical or mental harm or even death.
[normal]32
[normal]. 
[normal]In our view any system which requires the provider to obtain proof of lawful residence for a period of a year will be wholly unworkable both because of practical difficulties in obtaining such evi
[normal]dence and also due to the complexities as to who is ‘lawfully’ resident (and for a year). If this proposal is implemented there will be practical difficulties in obtaining proof and providers will be risk averse because of reasons given above.
[normal]33
[normal]. 
[normal]We are c
[normal]oncerned that the legal aid provider would need to gather the evidence in all cases, including people who are extremely vulnerable per se but also whose circumstances mean that they cannot easily find their own paperwork. Many people, particularly those wh
[normal]o have chaotic lifestyles or disabilities, or who are in a time of crisis do not readily have access to documentary evidence of lawful residence. Even if, which we doubt, this client group could provide evidence of lawful residence for a year, the delay in
[normal] producing the evidence prior to accessing legal advice would place them at very serious risk and may in some cases lead to their suffering harm or even death because of the administrative requirements.
[normal]34
[normal]. 
[normal]The complexity around the term ‘lawfully 
[normal]resident’ will result in confusion, people being denied advice to which they are entitled, and second guessing by the LAA. This in turn will
[normal], judging from past experience on e.g. financial eligibility evidence, 
[normal]lead to considerable additional expense for t
[normal]he LAA in auditing firms, appeals and other challenges, something recognised by the original Impact 
[normal]Assessment. We think that this has been seriously underestimated and will create massive problems for the efficient operation of the legal aid scheme.
[normal]35
[normal]. 
[normal]A
[normal]dditionally this is time which providers can ill afford to spend on administrative matters when businesses are already under extreme pressure
[normal].
[normal]36
[normal]. 
[normal]It is already difficult for people who are entitled to legal aid to satisfy the eligibility test because of i
[normal]ts increased complexity following 
[normal]the 
[normal]LASPO
[normal] 
[normal]A
[normal]ct
[normal]. The residence test will make it even more difficult for people to obtain legal aid, even if under this new test they are lawfully entitled to do so.
[normal] 
[normal]This is a non-evidence based proposal 
[normal]and 
[normal]the Government h
[normal]as shown no logical or defensible reason for its introduction. It is flawed on every level. 
[normal]37. British Citizens who have not lived here for the last 12 months will have to show proof they have previously lived here for a period of 12 months which provide
[normal]rs need to check, which for people who have lived abroad, possibly with their partner's job, may find very hard to prove. 
[normal]38
[normal]. 
[normal]The Government has acknowledged that it does not have data on the numbers of people affected by this proposal. It cannot cost it,
[normal] 
[normal]either 
[normal]in terms of any savings to the legal aid fund or the additional cost to society from removal of access to legal aid.
[normal]39
[normal]. 
[normal]The Government 
[normal]has no evidence to say that this proposal is needed to shore up public confidence. There is no evidence that acc
[normal]ess to legal advice is a cause of unlawful entry or residence in the UK (and this would be most surprising). Public confidence in the legal aid system could be fostered by the Government explaining to the public what legal aid remains available for, and th
[normal]e fact that already only a very small percentage of the population is eligible for any legal advice at any level.
[normal]4
[normal]0
[normal]. As we stated in our response to the consultation, the effects of the LASPO cuts have yet to be evaluated but it was anticipated that they 
[normal]will result in over 600,000 people a year being denied access to justice. The LASPO 
[normal]Act 
[normal]cuts left a rump of a legal aid system accessible to a very small minority of the poorest and most vulnerable in society. The residence proposal will ensure that the po
[normal]orest and most vulnerable of those, many of them lawfully and properly in the UK, will also now be excluded from access to justice. This proposal is not a transformation. It is a cut of the most politically cynical ‘slash and burn’ variety. 
